				\begin{document}$${\Gamma }_{1}$$\end{document} symmetry is one-photon allowed when polarized along the direction of symmetry breaking. More drastically, in a monoclinic system that belongs to the Cs point group that lacks inversion symmetry, all exciton states are both one and two-photon allowed (see Supplementary Note 1 and Supplementary Figs. 3 and 4). Thus, in a general sense we may monitor the presence or absence of symmetry breaking in a given semiconductor by the presence or absence of an overlap between one- and two-photon allowed transitions at ℏω\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
