				\begin{document}$$2\hslash \omega \approx 2.20\;{{{{{\rm{eV}}}}}}$$\end{document}. A corresponding feature in the absorption spectrum is observed at approximately at the same energy. Such a second band has been observed by numerous methods in the literature, including absorption40, ellipsometry41, and pump-probe spectroscopy42, and most interpretations have considered a transition involving higher energy conduction-bands, or a contribution from a valley along another symmetry axis in the BZ41,43.

